<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-831-047  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 831 047.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 8 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Dramatic change proposed in high-tech exports to U.S.S.R.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woods, Wendy.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryInternational tradeSoviet UnionGovernment RegulationTechnology Transfer.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DRAMATIC CHANGE PROPOSED IN HIGH-TECH EXPORTS TO U.S.S.R.andP;  WASHINGTON, D.C.,andO;U.S.A., 1990 MAY 5 (NB) -- The Bush Administration has issued a sweeping newrecommendation which, if passed by COCOM (Coordinating Committee forMultilateral Export Controls), would make a significant change in the list oftechnologies subject to export control.andM;The proposals &quot;build higher fences around fewer goods,&quot; according to astatement by the White House press secretary, and specifically make legal theexport of more types of computers and telecommunications equipment to theSoviet Union and Eastern Europe.andM;Computers that would be free of controls are technically categorized as thoseoperating below a 275 megabit per second level of performance.andP;  Thisdecontrols virtually all personal computers commonly used in officeautomation, word processing, and light industry, and includes such models asthe IBM 400 and 4381 MG 13 series, Control Data's Cyber 840, DigitalEquipment VAX 8600s and the Hewlett-Packard 3000 machines.andM;The proposal also provides for favorable consideration of licenses submittedto COCOM for mainframe computers up to a performance level of 550 megabitsper second.andM;Among telecommunications equipment proposed for decontrol are satelliteground stations for civil television and communications to permit Westernbroadcasting in Eastern Europe; civil mobile radio including trunked radiotelephone, paging, dispatch and the current analog radio cellular systems;and civil packet switching systems up to the level currently being exportedto China.andM;The Bush Administration says that once Eastern European countries adoptsafeguards to protect against diversion of equipment to proscribed countries,export of fiber optic transmission equipment with transmission rates up to156 megabits per second will generally be permitted.andM;A White House statement says, &quot;Based on thorough analysis by the Departmentsof State, Defense, Commerce, and Energy, the proposals reflect the changingstrategic threat and provide for increased access to advanced technology,particularly to the emerging democracies of Eastern Europe.&quot;andM;The proposal will be formally made in the first week of June to COCOM at itsformal meeting in Paris.andP;  If accepted by that body, the new regulations couldgo into effect several months later.andM;(Wendy Woods/19900505)</TEXT></DOC>